<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The Stock Market Crash of 1929 was significant because it:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Was quickly resolved by government action</option>
            <option letter="b">Marked the beginning of the Great Depression</option>
            <option letter="c">Only affected wealthy investors</option>
            <option letter="d">Strengthened international trade</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Stock Market Crash of October 1929 marked the beginning of the Great Depression. The crash wiped out billions in wealth, destroyed investor confidence, and triggered a chain reaction of bank failures, business closures, and unemployment. While not the sole cause of the Depression, the crash symbolized the end of 1920s prosperity and the beginning of the worst economic crisis in American history.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
